				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>admin wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">But on the other side, the second idea of sending notifications is to give an incentive to <a href="https://www.plimus.com/jsp/buynow.jsp?contractId=1671485" target="_blank" class="postlink">sponsor me</a>.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Hi, Oleg,
<br />
For me, it seems to be a very strange idea to write a GPL code awaiting to be sponsored. I think in the GPL world the only sponsoring is restricted to the information and feedback (something like collecting spambot's IPs) I think if one wants to be sponsored, he would better do like  mister Gates does. But you might have your own reasoning...
<br />

<br />
Well, since one week that your textual confirmation is inserted in my phpbb it rejects about 90% spambots. Looking through mailings, I found that remaining  10% registrations have already been rejected at least once. It was the second (or the 3rd) registration that has been accepted. Hence, they read and collect the phpbb answer in order to understand why they registration has been rejected. So I am thinking whether it would be preferrable to hide the true reason and to write something general (&quot;We do not need spambots, your registration is rejected&quot;) or false (like simple &quot;PhpBB error&quot;).
<br />

<br />
Third thing: It seems also to be a good idea to hide website and language fields in the registration form and reject all registrations with websites and lang=english. If the default language of the forum must be english, it must be renamed in this case.  
<br />

<br />
After these changes have been applied I have zero spambots  in 3 days and about 100 rejections a day.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
